{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/skin-cancers-recognition-referral/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"e6ee527d-5fc4-5ac8-940b-93f94ac104a6","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 9f041918-2d44-4458-b7b9-75a17e61729f --><h1>Skin cancers - recognition and referral: Summary</h1><!-- end field 9f041918-2d44-4458-b7b9-75a17e61729f -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 30c3f645-e6c9-42ed-bed4-2135b5a6a2d7 --><!-- begin field 69200d8f-45fb-4730-8125-7cdc3576451f --><ul><li>Melanoma of the skin — just over 13,000 new melanomas are diagnosed each year in the UK. A full time GP is likely to diagnose approximately one person with melanoma every 3–5 years. The 5 year survival is 90%.</li><li>Refer people using a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for melanoma if they have a suspicious pigmented skin lesion with a weighted 7-point checklist score of 3 or more.</li><li>Refer people using a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) if dermoscopy suggests melanoma of the skin.</li><li>Consider a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for melanoma in people with a pigmented or non-pigmented skin lesion that suggests nodular melanoma.</li><li>Squamous cell carcinoma — approximately 25,000 squamous cell carcinomas of the skin are diagnosed each year. A full time GP is likely to diagnose at least one person with squamous cell carcinoma every 1–2 years. Death from squamous cell carcinoma is rare. The main advantage of early diagnosis is less extensive treatment.</li><li>Consider a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for people with a skin lesion that raises the suspicion of squamous cell carcinoma.</li><li>Basal cell carcinoma — approximately 75,000 basal cell carcinomas of the skin are diagnosed each year. A full time GP is likely to diagnose at least one person with basal cell carcinoma per year. Death from basal cell carcinoma is exceptionally rare. The main advantage from early diagnosis is less extensive treatment.</li><li>Consider routine referral for people if they have a skin lesion that raises the suspicion of a basal cell carcinoma.</li><li>Only consider a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for people with a skin lesion that raises the suspicion of a basal cell carcinoma if there is particular concern that a delay may have a significant impact, because of factors such as lesion site or size.</li></ul><!-- end field 69200d8f-45fb-4730-8125-7cdc3576451f --><!-- end item 30c3f645-e6c9-42ed-bed4-2135b5a6a2d7 -->","topic":{"id":"b5e958f7-3b89-58c9-948d-c9405fa255f1","topicId":"dabd3469-1c63-4dec-83b4-28c443c7d5c3","topicName":"Skin cancers - recognition and referral","slug":"skin-cancers-recognition-referral","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"e6ee527d-5fc4-5ac8-940b-93f94ac104a6","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"ebef9550-592f-5898-8ba3-9ea38bb51c17","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"b3e81aa2-1b6a-5eee-92a5-4f0591335062","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"a4d2fff4-bef2-5d6b-908a-5857d3524985","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"f271a541-7dd3-570a-b689-00c0ed3f49cd","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"6ab1ee1c-d33f-5ca5-a1aa-164a4dfd7590","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"fdcb91b4-39e3-5e03-9ba0-8408c9b26787","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"d4f6d2c2-6eac-5296-8598-6c238dde918f","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"4ca236ab-c8af-5074-813f-6751f92b4952","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"453c2ce2-aae0-54e6-b588-f050c8756fc8","slug":